      <div xml:id="NA14-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iyaṟpaḻitta tōḻikkut talaivi iyaṟpaṭa moḻintatu. (ETv: itu talaivi iyaṟpaṭa moḻintatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE said in [his] favour when the confidante was belittling [his] qualities.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA14">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>          tolkaviṉ ṟolaiyat tōṇalañ cāya</l>
<l>          nalkār nīttaṉa rāyiṉu nalkuvar</l>
<l>          naṭṭaṉar vāḻi tōḻi kuṭṭuva</l>
<l>          ṉakappā vaḻiya nūṟic cempiyaṉ</l>
<l>          pakaṟṟī vēṭṭa ñāṭpiṉu mikapperi </l>
<l>          talareḻac ceṉṟaṉa rāyiṉu malarkavintu</l>
<l>          māmaṭa laviḻnta kāntaḷañ cāraliṉ </l>
<l>          ñālvāyk kaḷiṟu pāntaṭ paṭṭeṉat</l>
<l>          tuñcāt tuyarat tañcupiṭip pūca</l>
<l>          ṉeṭuvarai viṭarakat tiyampuṅ </l>
<l>          kaṭumāṉ pulliya kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
  <l rend="indent2">Even if he left, not one to grant [his presence],</l>
	<l rend="indent">so that [my] old beauty is lost, [my] shoulders' goodness exhausted,</l>
	<l rend="indent4">he is one who grants.</l>
  <l>He did befriend [us], oh friend,</l>
  <l>– he who traversed the wilderness of Pulli of fast horses,</l>
	<l rend="indent">where the clamour of the fearful she-elephant, sleepless with misery,</l>
	<l rend="indent2">resounds inside the caves of the long mountain,</l>
	<l rend="indent3">as the serpent has come over<note place="foot">T.V.G. connects this with the topos of the python swallowing an elephant; cf. NA 261.6.</note> the elephant bull with hanging mouth,</l>
	<l rend="indent4">on the slope of Malabar lilies which opened [among] big fronds</l>
	<l rend="indent4">[their] covering blossoms,<note place="foot">Literally "on which the blossoms, covering [the surface], open on the stems".</note></l>
	<l rend="indent4">even if he went so that gossip arose,</l>
	<l rend="indent3">much louder than the battle, where Cempiyaṉ</l>
	<l rend="indent3">completely<note place="foot">Here T.V.G. thinks that <term xml:lang="ta">Cempiyaṉ</term> first destroyed <term xml:lang="ta">Akappā</term> and then sacrificed, an issue not overtly supported by the wording. But since the comparison is for the noise, the point might rather be the sound of the burning fortress.</note> demolished Kuṭṭuvaṉ's [fort] Akappā</l>
	<l rend="indent4">[and] made [it] a sacrifice to the fire by midday.</l>
        
</lg>
         </div>
